[normal]2.2 
[normal]On the basis of the track record of F
[normal]oundation 
[normal]T
[normal]rust
[normal]s i
[normal]n recent years, the 
[normal]Annual Plan Review indicates the sector will continue to be resilient in the short term
[normal].  However, we know that the
[normal] number of foundation trusts
[normal] in financial distress has increased, as has the number struggli
[normal]ng to meet operational demands.  T
[normal]he outlook on overall funding is uncertain and the spending review has confirmed that financial pressures will increase beyond 201
[normal]5/16.
[normal]  The review 
[normal]suggests the balance of longer term ris
[normal]ks has shifted to the downside.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 
[normal]Tariff deflation, combined with inflation of costs, drives the need for year-on-year efficiency savings and increas
[normal]es the financial stress on the foundation trust
[normal] s
[normal]ector.
[normal] 
[normal] This is most markedly demonstrated by a decline in the overall sector EBITDA (earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortisation) 
[normal]percentage 
[normal]– a key measure of cashflow - from 7.1% in 2009/10 to 6.0% in 2012/13.
